## Understanding Optimization Levels

### Common GCC/Clang Flags

| Flag | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `-O0` | No optimization (default) |
| `-O1` | Basic optimizations |
| `-O2` | Standard optimizations (good balance) |
| `-O3` | Aggressive optimizations (may increase code size) |
| `-Os` | Optimize for size |
| `-Ofast` | `-O3` plus fast-math and other aggressive options |

### What to Look For

When comparing assembly outputs across scenarios:

1. **Loop unrolling** - Higher optimization levels may unroll loops
2. **Inlining** - Functions may be inlined at higher levels
3. **Dead code elimination** - Unused code is removed
4. **Register allocation** - Better register usage at higher levels
5. **Instruction selection** - More efficient instructions chosen
